Accordingly, when we came upon the Coats of Spain, he ent the nine Spaniards Prioners to Sevil; and though I begg'd him to let me accompany Atolfo, he kept me at Sea a few days more, and then Landed me at Aveiro, and gave me a preent to a Wife he had there. It would be tedious for me to tell you, how ill I bore this wort change of my Fortune; I raged,


I grieved, till my Sighs and Tears grew o thick upon one another, that no one could know which was the mot plentiful of their two Fountains, my Heart, or my Eyes. My Mitres, who was a good natur'd Gentlewoman, intereed her elf in my Sorrows, and would often enquire what was the reaon of my grieving; till at lat her Importunities drew from me the whole Relation, which I have now made to you; he bade me be comforted, and think no more of him; I told her I could not be atisfied without him: That opinion (ays he) is, I hope, a fale one; you mut be comforted either without him, or not at all, for you mut never expect to ee him again; for uppoing he hould ecape, being condemned to the Gallies, yet how is it likely that you, who are a Stranger, hould find out a ingle Man, and one of no note, in uch a large City as Sevill, or one who perhaps, before you could get thither, would be gone to ome other part of the World? I told her I had an Art, by which I could do more than that; and thus much I knew, that if I were at my liberty, and had a little travelling Money, I hould not be a year e're I found him She asked what Art that was: 'Tis what I learned


from my Father, (aid I) and is very common among us: She deired to ee the effects of it; I told her I would hew it, in reolving whatever quetion he would ask me. She bade me tell her where her Husband was at that time, and when he would come home:
